She flipped to a blank page and wrote down the date. Then, she wrote below the date: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'd let you go out for Christmas? There are only a few days left until Christmas."
Carly tapped twice on the lantern, indicating "no." As Avery expected. The Ice King never allowed Carly to go outside, because in his eyes, Carly was "a flaw." Carly was born mute and was the only girl in the family, while all the other children were boys.
Avery was the same, in their own unique way. When Avery publicly appeared as a non-binary person, the world seemed to change. As punishment for being different, they were mostly assigned to work alone most of the time.
They were also forced to be the princess's servant. However, they didn't mind, because they had a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up, right?" Avery asked, remembering that in a few more days it would be the princess's birthday. Carly nodded, a hint of sadness flashing in her light blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate it?" TA asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
No. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew this was a difficult topic for Carly to bring up. On that day, she was imprisoned in this room while her mother was executed. When it happened, Avery was still an infant, but TA remembered the anger of the servants and the citizens. TA had heard that Queen Alvin was a good queen, and could miraculously predict future events.
"Then... what would you like to do?" TA asked. Carly looked up at TA, excited. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down...
6 inches X 6 inches canvas
White, shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Are you trying to ask me to get these things for you?" Avery turned to the silent princess, who was constantly tapping and her ponytail swaying back and forth. "Right?" When TA saw this usually quiet princess so enthusiastic about something, TA couldn't help but giggle. This was the first time she wanted something outside of her room, and it had nothing to do with books.
"Okay! Then see you later?" Avery said, standing up and walking through the mess of papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to curl up in the thick blanket, reviewing her memories.
TA left the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try new things and had made some requests beyond her capabilities (such as paint).
TA crossed the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the maids' whispered conversations.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Alvin, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, is that normal?"
TA really couldn't stand hearing these words anymore, so TA covered their ears. TA went to the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Avery arrived at that door, which was as elaborately decorated as Carly's door. A white dragon was painted on the door, one of the six original dragons, said to be the one that created the Frostlands. It's no wonder the painter, who loved history, painted the white dragon on the door.
TA opened the door, expecting everything to be as usual. For example, there were plenty of paints, pencils, and papers scattered everywhere, and easels covered every inch of the walls. Unexpectedly, the scene inside the room was completely different. The room was clean, with a red velvet backdrop and a chair. Sitting on the chair was Crown Prince Aquero, who was painting a portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Avery! Would you like to see a portrait of your future king?" Aquero asked, winking at Avery.
"I'm sorry, Prince," TA replied, beginning to look around for the things Princess Carly wanted. "I just came to get some art supplies."
"Little darling, leaving so soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I still wanted to see you!"
"I don't want to," Avery found the art supplies on the list and put them into a box. "And I'm not a girl anyway."
The prince dismissed this. "Oh, darling, you know this is just a phase! It'll be fine when you grow up!" he mumbled incoherently.
"I need to go," TA said, suddenly feeling uncomfortable because the prince was still talking nonstop. TA recalled all the negative comments people had made about TA's gender identity. I really want to get rid of him.
"So soon you're leaving?" The prince instantly appeared at the door, ignoring the royal painter's shouts.
"This is not the behavior of a future king!" TA scolded sternly.
"No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still cares about his life, he won't say anything either." The prince glanced back at the painter and then leaned in close to Avery. "What do you think of the date?" TA trembled in fear. Of course, TA had heard many threats before, but none of them were from the prince, let alone from this future king.
"Do you even know what the word 'no' means?" TA shouted angrily, shoving the prince aside.
"No." Aquilo replied with a smile. This prince, who could get whatever he wanted, certainly didn't know what the word "no" meant.
Avery rolled her eyes. "Why are there so many people, and you specifically want to go on a date with me? How many admirers do you have? A hundred?"
He interrupted with a smile: "To be precise, more than five hundred." He shook his hair, swaying in the cold wind.
"See! Why me? I'm a disaster in the palace." TA hugged his arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aguero placed a finger under Avery's chin, forcing her to look up at him.
